[0.012, "o", "\u001b[1;2H\u001b[44X\n This is the main Apache HTTP server configuration file.  It contains the\u001b[3;2H configuration directives that give the server its instructions.\u001b[4;2H See <URL:http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/> for detailed information.\u001b[5;2H In particular, see \u001b[36X\u001b[6;2H <URL:http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/mod/directives.html>\u001b[7X\u001b[7;2H for a discussion of each configuration directive.\u001b[10X\u001b[8;2H\u001b[50X\n Do \u001b[0;10;1m\u000fNOT\u001b[m\u000f simply read the instructions in here without understanding\u001b[10;2H what they do.  They're here only as hints or reminders.  If you are unsure\u001b[11;2H consult the online docs. You have been warned.  \u001b[12;2H\u001b[42X\n Configuration and logfile names: If the filenames you specify for many\u001b[14;2H of the server's control files begin with \"/\" (or \"drive:/\" for Win32), the\u001b[15;2H server will use that explicit path.  If the filenames do *not* begin\r\n# with \"/\", the value of ServerRoot is prepended -- so \"logs/access_log\"\u001b[17;2H with ServerRoot set to \"/usr/local/apache2\" will be interpreted by the\u001b[18;2H server as \"/usr/local/apache2/logs/access_log\", whereas \"/logs/access_log\" \r\n# will be interpreted as '/logs/access_log'.    \r\n\u001b[46X\u001b[21;2H\u001b[52X\n ServerRoot: The top of the directory tree under which the server's\u001b[23;2H configuration, error, and log files are kept.\u001b[24;2H\u001b[58X\n Do not add a slash at the end of the directory path.  If you point\u001b[26;2H ServerRoot at a non-local disk, be sure to specify a local disk on the\u001b[27;2H Mutex directive, if file-based mutexes are used.  If you wish to share the\u001b[28;2H same ServerRoot for multiple httpd daemons, you will need to change at\r\n# least PidFile.\u001b[26X\u001b[30;2H\u001b[42X\r\n\u001b[96mServerRoot\u001b[m\u000f \u001b[92m\"/etc/httpd\"\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[31X\r\n\u001b[53X\u001b[33;2H\u001b[58X\n Mutex: Allows you to set the mutex mechanism and mutex file directory\u001b[35;2H for individual mutexes, or change the global defaults\r\n#\u001b[39X\n Uncomment and change the directory if mutexes are file-based and the default\u001b[38;2H mutex file directory is not on a local disk or is not ap\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpro\u001b[m\u000fpriate for some\u001b[39;2H other reason.\u001b[34X\r\n#\u001b[47X\n Mutex default:/run/httpd\u001b[19X\r\n\u001b[53X\u001b[43;2H\u001b[52X\r\n# Listen: Allows you to bind Apache to specific IP addresses and/or\r\n# ports, instead of the default. See also the <VirtualHost>\u001b[46;2H directive.\u001b[39X\r\n#\u001b[43X\n Change this to Listen on specific IP addresses as shown below to \u001b[49;2H prevent Apache from glomming onto all bound IP addresses.\u001b[50;2H\u001b[54X\r\n#Listen 12.34.56.78:80\u001b[32X\r\n\u001b[96mListen\u001b[m\u000f 80\u001b[46X\r\n\u001b[57X\u001b[54;2H\u001b[58X\u001b[55;183H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f38,59          Top\u001b[56;5H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.022, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \b"]
[0.012, "o", "\u001b[16;40H\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpr\u001b[17;60Hpr\u001b[19;16Hpr\u001b[38;59Hpr\u001b[m\u000fo\u001b[30m\u001b[103mpr\u001b[49;3Hpr\u001b[55;183H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f16,40\u001b[56;4H\u001b[?25h"]
